        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/5/35a633/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-12-21T13:36:58.862Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"dibanez\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"5280\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/2acd7d/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> dibanez:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>get messages for a certain group</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Depending on what you are trying to accomplish, there are some unofficial projects that are starting to address this use-case.  They are not officially supported, and are very early in their creation (from 2017 or 2018 mostly), but it might be easier than rolling your own  code at the libsignal-service level, to see if joining one of the existing unofficial projects will do what you need.  See the list at <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/signals-complementary-downstream-projects-please-list-them-here/5093\" class=\"inline-onebox\">Signal's complementary downstream projects - please list them here</a></p>\n<p>In particular, if you are looking for a kind of chatbot-type way to add an automated “member” of groupchats, which can programmatically participate and respond within the groupchat, take at look at sigd and ionosphere, both of those were implemented with such use-cases in mind.  If you do not have a linux system available, you can either get a VPS for a few dollars a month, or you can run a linux distro as a guest-OS inside a virtual machine on your preferred operating system, if you like.</p>\n<p>What is the goal here, with getting access to groupchat messages via an API, that you are trying to accomplish?  Knowing that will help us better advise you</p>",
