        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/5/35a633/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-12-24T12:41:05.096Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Yup, those are backend embedded-jetty URL endpoints that the official signal-server codebase exposes at the SIGNAL_URL specified in build.gradle on signal4android APKs (and if you setup your own custom signal4server instance you would alter the YML and certs and compile it… and then alter a few places in the APK including certs and base-url and then hand-compile it as well).</p>\n<pre>CREATE_ACCOUNT_SMS_PATH   \t= \"/v1/accounts/sms/code/%s?client=%s\";\nCREATE_ACCOUNT_VOICE_PATH \t= \"/v1/accounts/voice/code/%s\";\nVERIFY_ACCOUNT_CODE_PATH  \t= \"/v1/accounts/code/%s\";\nREGISTER_GCM_PATH             \t= \"/v1/accounts/gcm/\";\nTURN_SERVER_INFO              \t= \"/v1/accounts/turn\";\nSET_ACCOUNT_ATTRIBUTES    \t= \"/v1/accounts/attributes/\";\nPIN_PATH                                 \t= \"/v1/accounts/pin/\";\n\nPREKEY_METADATA_PATH      \t= \"/v2/keys/\";\nPREKEY_PATH                        \t= \"/v2/keys/%s\";\nPREKEY_DEVICE_PATH            \t= \"/v2/keys/%s/%s\";\nSIGNED_PREKEY_PATH          \t= \"/v2/keys/signed\";\n\nPROVISIONING_CODE_PATH    \t= \"/v1/devices/provisioning/code\";\nPROVISIONING_MESSAGE_PATH \t= \"/v1/provisioning/%s\";\nDEVICE_PATH                         \t= \"/v1/devices/%s\";\n\nDIRECTORY_TOKENS_PATH     \t= \"/v1/directory/tokens\";\nDIRECTORY_VERIFY_PATH     \t= \"/v1/directory/%s\";\nDIRECTORY_AUTH_PATH       \t= \"/v1/directory/auth\";\nMESSAGE_PATH                      \t= \"/v1/messages/%s\";\nSENDER_ACK_MESSAGE_PATH   \t= \"/v1/messages/%s/%d\";\nUUID_ACK_MESSAGE_PATH     \t= \"/v1/messages/uuid/%s\";\nATTACHMENT_PATH                 \t= \"/v1/attachments/%s\";\n\nPROFILE_PATH                        \t= \"/v1/profile/%s\";\nSENDER_CERTIFICATE_PATH   \t= \"/v1/certificate/delivery\";\n</pre>\n<p>All that stuff is therefore exposed, in between the APK of signal4android, and the matching signal4server node, via HTTPS.</p>\n<p>So in theory there could be a REST API, but in practice it is 100% considered officially undocumented, officially unsupported, and can be changed at any time in non-backwards-compatible fashion.  This is related to the position that OWS and Signal Foundation have staked out with respect to federation of server-side nodes.  It slows down development too much, if you have to worry about federating with servers that are not under your control.  Similarly, I suspect the reason for the lack of an official REST API, is that it is perceived as slowing down development too much, when one hypothetically has to worry about breaking downstream projects which rely upon the “old” API semantics/helpdocs/etc.</p>\n<p>If you are interested in programmatically interacting with signal4server, then you will be doing it 100% unofficially and 100% unsupported, as far as posting to github and emailing <a href=\"mailto:support@signal.org\">support@signal.org</a> are concerned, in other words.  You can get friendly help here in the signalUsers forum, from your fellow extra-passionate-about-signalapp folks.  And there have been several questions about writing a chatbot, or equivalent.  Telegram has bots and a client-SDK, slack has bots, and so on.  But signalapp for various unspecified reasons does not – that I am aware at least… if anybody has a link to any semi-official comment on the reason for a lack of an API and lack of an SDK and lack of scripting-control from the client-side world, I would appreciate seeing the rationale.</p>\n<p>So, if you are just wanting to make a read-only bot, which retrieves groupchat messages, then yes the most easily-supported approach is to setup one of the existing projects (all unofficial mind you!) which allows you to programmatically control a phone-number.  This typically means installing sig4cli by AsamK onto your system, getting a phone number to register it with the official signal-servers (can be landline or voip like google voice or various other things… need not be cell-num or even “your” number but you DO need to maintain control over the phone-number in question to prevent an adversary getting control of your signal-identifier).  That is a long-running unofficial project, since at least 2014 methinks.  Alternatively, in your specific case you might prefer the newer projects sigd and ionosphere-slash-sig4hubot (also unofficial) which are also in <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/signals-complementary-downstream-projects-please-list-them-here/5093\">the same downstream-project-list</a> as sig4cli (linked previously).</p>\n<p>And you may find that none of those three does what you REALLY are wanting, and end up rolling your own codebase to implement your groupchat-backup-and-monitoring-readonly-bot, in which case you can use libsignal-service-java (which is official code but also officially unsupported … except here in signalUsers of course).  You might also prefer to utilize the longstanding <a href=\"https://github.com/signal-csharp/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">unofficial libsigSvc4dotnet</a> (currently aimed at C# but other dotnet langs are plausible), or the newer <a href=\"https://github.com/throneless-tech/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">unofficial libsigSvc4js</a> (currently NodeJS but eventually aims to be ecmaScript-compatible as well).</p>\n<p>If you are happy with the platforms supported (OS and programming language) of the existing CLI-scripting-and-chatbot-oriented projects, they are a good place to start.  If you prefer to roll your own, that is also possible.</p>\n<p>p.s.  And you may decide that, rather than going with the route of installing and/or modifying such things for groupchat access, the more direct route is preferable:  you could, assuming your own signal4smartphone is a group-member, modify the client-codebase to add the “make a backup of this groupchat” feature to your member-device.  If you prefer, you can link your signal4smartphone to a slave-device running signal4desktop (win/lin/osx laptop or server), and then modify the codebase there to hand-compile your own signal4desktop with a “backup this groupchat” option provided internally.</p>\n<p>If you do go this route… of adding a client-side feature rather than of using an unofficial chatbot… and you make the groupchat backups feature produce <strong>encrypted</strong> blobs, in the same way that the existing signal4android can produce whole-chat-history-encrypted-backup-blobs, you might even be able to get your feature-implementation upstreamed.  Just try to make your “partial encrypted backup” feature minimally invasive, and make sure you get copyright-sign-off from all contributors (and only rely upon codebases where you have 100% copyright-control … upstream is dual-licensed and requires all code-contribs to be CLA’d prior to merging).</p>\n<p>This <strong>is</strong> the pathway I would recommend, if you have the time and inclination and skillset.  It would be more work than simply installing the hubot-framework or sigd or whatever, in the short run, but if you succeed in getting the ‘just backup this groupchat’ feature added to official clients, in the long run you would be able to let signal foundation maintain the codebase for you.  And I suspect that modifying the existing signal4android backup-codebase, to selectively produce a single groupchat backup-blob (they all have a threadid) would be a fairly straightforward upgrade, if you are familiar with android studio at least.</p>\n<p>Keep us filled in on the details of your effort, please, and which pathway you decide to pursue… plus whether you run into any obstacles or enjoy any victories of course :-)</p>",
